## Complete Express API Route & Handler Analysis

I've explored all route files and handlers in this Express API project. Here's the complete breakdown:

### **Project Structure Overview**

**File Locations:**
- `/src/app.ts` - Main Express application setup
- `/src/server.ts` - Server entry point
- `/src/types.ts` - TypeScript interfaces
- `/src/db.ts` - In-memory database with test data
- `/src/routes/posts.ts` - Posts routes
- `/src/routes/comments.ts` - Comments routes
- `/src/middleware/logger.ts` - Logging middleware

---

### **1. Application Setup (`src/app.ts`)**

```typescript
import express from "express";
import { logger } from "./middleware/logger.js";
import { postsRouter } from "./routes/posts.js";
import { commentsRouter } from "./routes/comments.js";

const app = express();

app.use(express.json());
app.use(logger);

// Routes
app.use("/posts", postsRouter);
app.use(commentsRouter);

// Health check
app.get("/health", (req, res) => {
  res.json({ status: "ok" });
});

export { app };
```

**Key Points:**
- Global middleware: `express.json()` for parsing JSON body and custom `logger` middleware
- Posts router mounted at `/posts` prefix
- Comments router mounted at root (routes handle full paths internally)
- Health check endpoint at `/health`

---

### **2. Logging Middleware (`src/middleware/logger.ts`)**

```typescript
import { Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";

export function logger(req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction): void {
  const start = Date.now();
  res.on("finish", () => {
    const duration = Date.now() - start;
    console.log(`${req.method} ${req.path} ${res.statusCode} - ${duration}ms`);
  });
  next();
}
```

**Middleware Pattern:**
- Captures request start time
- Logs method, path, status code, and duration after response finishes
- Calls `next()` to pass control to next middleware/route

---

### **3. Posts Routes (`src/routes/posts.ts`) - COMPLETE**

```typescript
import { Router } from "express";
import { posts, nextId } from "../db.js";
import { Post } from "../types.js";

const router = Router();

// GET /posts - list all posts
router.get("/", (req, res) => {
  res.json(posts);
});

// GET /posts/:id - get a single post
router.get("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const post = posts.find((p) => p.id === id);
  if (!post) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  res.json(post);
});

// POST /posts - create a new post
router.post("/", (req, res) => {
  const { title, content, userId } = req.body;
  if (!title || !content) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: "title and content are required" });
    return;
  }
  const newPost: Post = {
    id: nextId(posts),
    title,
    content,
    userId: userId || 1,
    createdAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };
  posts.push(newPost);
  res.status(201).json(newPost);
});

// PUT /posts/:id - update a post
router.put("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const { title, content } = req.body;
  if (title) posts[index].title = title;
  if (content) posts[index].content = content;
  res.json(posts[index]);
});

// DELETE /posts/:id - delete a post
router.delete("/:id", (req, res) => {
  const id = parseInt(req.params.id, 10);
  const index = posts.findIndex((p) => p.id === id);
  if (index === -1) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: "Post not found" });
    return;
  }
  const deleted = posts.splice(index, 1);
  res.json(deleted[0]);
});

export { router as postsRouter };
```

**Route Patterns:**
- GET all: `router.get("/", ...)` - returns entire array
- GET by ID: `router.get("/:id", ...)` - extracts from `req.params.id`
- POST create: `router.post("/", ...)` - extracts from `req.body` with validation
- PUT update: `router.put("/:id", ...)` - partial updates from `req.body`
- DELETE: `router.delete("/:id", ...)` - removes and returns deleted item

**Request Data Access:**
- Path params: `req.params.id` (string, parsed to int with `parseInt()`)
- Body data: `req.body.title`, `req.body.content`, `req.body.userId`

**Response Patterns:**
- Success: `res.json(data)` with implicit 200, or `res.status(201).json(data)` for creation
- Error: `res.status(404).json({ error: "..." })` or `res.status(400).json({ error: "..." })`
- All responses use `res.json()` for JSON serialization

---

### **4. Comments Routes (`src/routes/comments.ts`) - COMPLETE**

```typescript
